% ================= CHAPTER 4 =================
\chapter{RESULTS AND ANALYSIS}

This chapter presents the quantitative and qualitative outcomes of the AI-Enabled Home Planning and 3D Visualization Web Application. The system was evaluated across three core functional modules: semantic segmentation accuracy, cost prediction performance, and end-to-end processing latency. The experimental results confirm that the proposed multimodal AI pipeline successfully automates the conversion of hand-drawn floor plans into interactive 3D models with accurate cost forecasts.

\section{RESULTS}

\subsection{Segmentation Performance}

The PyTorch U-Net model was trained on a curated dataset of hand-drawn architectural floor plan sketches. The model demonstrated strong capability in accurately identifying and isolating structural wall regions from the complex and noisy backgrounds present in informal hand-drawn inputs.

During testing, the segmentation pipeline consistently produced clean binary masks that reliably separated wall pixels from void (open-space) regions across a wide variety of sketch styles. Sketches with thin, faint strokes were successfully enhanced by the OpenCV preprocessing stage through adaptive Gaussian thresholding and morphological dilation, ensuring that the U-Net received high-contrast, normalized input tensors.

The contracting path of the encoder effectively captured large-scale structural features such as room boundaries and wall junctions, while the expansive decoder, guided by skip connections, preserved fine-grained spatial detail during upsampling. This allowed the model to accurately delineate wall edges even in regions with overlapping or irregular hand-drawn lines.

The resulting semantic masks were geometrically clean and suitable for downstream vectorization using the Douglas-Peucker contour simplification algorithm, which successfully extracted room-level polygon coordinates for 3D synthesis. Overall, the segmentation module performed reliably across all tested floor plan configurations, producing consistent outputs that directly supported accurate 3D layout generation.

\subsection{Cost Prediction Performance}

The Scikit-Learn regression pipeline was evaluated using four candidate algorithms: Linear Regression, Decision Tree, Gradient Boosting, and Random Forest. Model selection was based on Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and coefficient of determination (R\textsuperscript{2}) computed on a held-out validation set.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Comparison of Regression Models for Construction Cost Prediction}
\label{tab:cost_model_comparison}
\begin{tabular}{|l|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{MAE (INR)} & \textbf{R\textsuperscript{2} Score} \\
\hline
Linear Regression & 1,42,300 & 0.81 \\
\hline
Decision Tree Regressor & 98,500 & 0.87 \\
\hline
Gradient Boosting Regressor & 74,200 & 0.92 \\
\hline
\textbf{Random Forest Regressor} & \textbf{61,800} & \textbf{0.95} \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The Random Forest Regressor achieved the lowest MAE of \texorpdfstring{\rupee}{}61,800 and the highest R\textsuperscript{2} score of 0.95, making it the selected production model. Its ensemble bagging strategy effectively reduced prediction variance introduced by irregular spatial metrics in hand-drawn sketches.

\subsection{System Processing Latency}

End-to-end processing time was benchmarked across 7 iterations, measuring the duration of each pipeline stage from sketch upload to delivery of all outputs to the frontend interface.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Performance Benchmarking Results (n=7 Iterations)}
\label{tab:latency}
\begin{tabular}{|l|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Processing Stage} & \textbf{Time (seconds)} \\
\hline
CV Preprocessing (OpenCV) & 0.028 \\
\hline
DL Inference (U-Net) & 0.028 \\
\hline
Layout Extraction (Vectorization) & 1.705 \\
\hline
3D Conversion (Three.js JSON) & 0.049 \\
\hline
\textbf{Total Pipeline} & \textbf{1.788} \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The benchmark results confirm an average total pipeline latency of \textbf{1.788 seconds}, with a minimum of 1.691 seconds and a maximum of 1.926 seconds across all iterations. The success rate across all 7 test runs was \textbf{100\%}. The layout extraction stage (1.705s) accounts for the majority of processing time due to contour simplification and JSON geometry generation. The asynchronous FastAPI subprocess orchestration ensures that the ML engines execute without blocking the frontend interface.

\section{ANALYSIS OF RESULTS}

The experimental results validate the effectiveness of the proposed multimodal AI framework across all evaluation dimensions.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Segmentation Accuracy:} The U-Net architecture, combined with the OpenCV preprocessing pipeline, reliably extracted structural walls from noisy hand-drawn sketches across all test cases. The adaptive Gaussian thresholding and morphological dilation operations effectively suppressed background noise and normalized stroke irregularities before inference. The encoder's contracting path successfully captured room-level structural context, while skip connections in the decoder ensured that fine wall boundaries were preserved during upsampling. The resulting binary masks were consistently clean, enabling accurate downstream contour extraction and 3D geometry generation.
    \item \textbf{Cost Prediction Precision:} The Random Forest model's R\textsuperscript{2} score of 0.95 indicates that 95\% of cost variance is explained by the spatial features extracted from the geometric JSON. The MAE of \texorpdfstring{INR 61,800}{INR 61,800} is within acceptable tolerance for conceptual-stage residential budget estimation.
    \item \textbf{Processing Efficiency:} The benchmarked average pipeline latency of 1.788 seconds (min: 1.691s, max: 1.926s across n=7 iterations) is well within the 5-second threshold expected for responsive web applications. The 100\% success rate across all test runs confirms that the FastAPI asynchronous architecture reliably parallelizes the AI inference pipeline without blocking the user interface or producing runtime failures.
    \item \textbf{Conversational Accuracy:} The Groq LLM chatbot produced contextually relevant design recommendations in all test interactions, successfully interpreting the spatial JSON metadata to provide room-specific suggestions regarding layouts, material choices, and budget optimization.
\end{itemize}

Overall, the system successfully bridges the gap between informal hand-drawn input and a fully functional, multi-output architectural intelligence platform, meeting all quantitative and qualitative objectives defined in Chapter 1.

% ================= CHAPTER 5 =================
\chapter{CONCLUSION}

This project successfully designed, developed, and deployed an AI-Enabled Home Planning and 3D Visualization Web Application that transforms informal hand-drawn floor plan sketches into interactive three-dimensional architectural models with integrated construction cost forecasting and conversational AI assistance.

The system demonstrated that a unified, multi-tier AI pipeline combining OpenCV image preprocessing, PyTorch U-Net semantic segmentation, Scikit-Learn regression-based cost prediction, Three.js WebGL rendering, and Groq LLM conversational intelligence can effectively automate the early-stage residential home planning workflow. The system achieved a cost prediction R\textsuperscript{2} of 0.95 and a benchmarked average end-to-end pipeline latency of just 1.788 seconds with a 100\% success rate across all test iterations, demonstrating that high-accuracy AI inference is achievable within the real-time constraints demanded by modern web applications.

The project fulfills all objectives defined in Chapter 1. Users can upload hand-drawn sketches and receive, within seconds, a fully rendered interactive 3D layout, a precise construction cost breakdown, and intelligent design recommendations — all without requiring specialized expertise in architectural software. This directly addresses the fragmentation and accessibility gaps identified in the literature review.

The modular, decoupled architecture ensures that individual components (vision pipeline, cost engine, chatbot) can be independently updated or replaced, providing a scalable foundation for future extensions.

% ================= CHAPTER 6 =================
\chapter{FUTURE SCOPE}

While the current system successfully achieves its defined objectives, several promising directions exist for extending and enhancing the platform in future iterations.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Augmented Reality (AR) Visualization:} Integrating AR frameworks such as WebXR or ARCore would enable users to project the generated 3D model into their real physical environment via mobile devices, providing an immersive spatial understanding beyond browser-based 3D rendering.
    \item \textbf{Object Detection for Furniture Placement:} Extending the computer vision pipeline with YOLO-based object detection would allow the system to identify doors, windows, and furniture outlines in uploaded sketches, enabling richer and more detailed 3D reconstruction.
    \item \textbf{BIM Export Integration:} Adding support for IFC (Industry Foundation Classes) or DXF export formats would allow the generated layouts to be imported into professional BIM tools such as Revit or AutoCAD, bridging the gap between conceptual planning and construction-grade documentation.
    \item \textbf{Multi-Storey and Site Planning:} Extending the current single-floor pipeline to support multi-storey floor plan stacking and site-level outdoor planning (gardens, driveways) would significantly broaden the system's applicability.
    \item \textbf{Real-Time Collaborative Design:} Implementing WebSocket-based multi-user sessions would allow architects and clients to collaboratively edit, annotate, and review the same 3D model simultaneously from different devices.
    \item \textbf{Refined Cost Models by Region:} Training region-specific cost regression models using localized construction material pricing datasets would improve the accuracy of construction estimates for geographically diverse users.
    \item \textbf{Voice-Controlled Chatbot Interface:} Integrating speech-to-text and text-to-speech capabilities would make the conversational AI assistant accessible to a broader audience, including users who prefer voice interaction over text input.
\end{itemize}

These enhancements would progressively elevate the platform from an academic prototype to a commercially viable architectural intelligence tool, capable of serving homeowners, designers, and construction professionals alike.

